Decision Log – Monday.com BI Agent
1. Key Assumptions
Several assumptions were made while designing and implementing the BI Agent.
Board structure consistency
I assumed that the monday.com boards would contain reasonably consistent column names for key business fields such as Sector, Execution Status, Deal Stage, and Deal Status. Since monday.com boards are flexible and customizable, the system includes simple safeguards such as checking whether a column exists before running an analysis.
Focus on common business questions
The agent was designed to answer common operational and leadership questions such as pipeline overview, sector performance, and execution status of work orders. These types of questions typically represent the information leadership teams request when reviewing business performance.
Real-time data access
The system retrieves live data from the monday.com API whenever a user asks a question. This ensures that insights generated by the agent reflect the most current data available in the boards.
Simple natural language interpretation is sufficient
Instead of implementing a full natural language processing system, a rule-based keyword interpretation approach was used to categorize user questions into a few predefined analysis types such as pipeline analysis, sector analysis, and execution status analysis. For the scope of this assignment, this approach provides a reliable and transparent way to interpret queries.
________________________________________
2. Trade-offs Chosen and Why
Several trade-offs were made to balance development speed, simplicity, and reliability.
Rule-based question interpretation vs advanced NLP
The agent uses keyword detection instead of a full NLP or LLM-based approach. This decision was made because rule-based interpretation is faster to implement, easier to debug, and deterministic. For a limited set of business questions, this method provides sufficient accuracy while keeping the architecture simple.
Direct API calls vs cached data
The agent retrieves data from the monday.com API each time a question is asked rather than storing cached datasets. This ensures that all analysis is based on the latest information available in the boards. The trade-off is slightly slower response times if the boards become large.
Streamlit interface vs custom frontend
The user interface was implemented using Streamlit rather than building a custom web frontend. Streamlit enables rapid prototyping, requires minimal infrastructure, and allows the agent to be deployed quickly as a hosted application. This approach ensures the evaluator can access and test the agent without any local setup.
